D: Refashioned:
We should not, however, fail to notice the difference between arguments that proceed from first principles and arguments that proceed toward them. Plato, too, was right to raise this question, asking whether we are on the road from first principles or toward them. There is a difference, just as in a racecourse between the course from the starting line to the turning post and the way back. While we must begin with what is known, things can be known in two senses: known to us, and known in an unqualified sense. Presumably, then, we must begin with things known to us. This is why anyone who is going to be a competent student of what is noble and just -- and of political science generally -- must have been brought up with good habits. For the fact is our starting point, and if the fact is sufficiently clear, there will be no need to ask for the reason behind it as well. The person who has been well brought up either already possesses these starting points or can easily acquire them. As for the person who neither has them nor can acquire them, let him hear the words of Hesiod:

'Far best is he who knows all things himself;
Good too is he who hearkens to wise counsel;
But he who neither knows nor takes to heart
Another's wisdom is a useless man.'
